the actual communication between client and server uses sockets over tcp/ip?

Analyzed communication mechanism between board client and server
Yes, exactly. The client opens a standard TCP socket and connects to an IP + port. Here's the precise path depending on the mode:

Board mode:


client  →  connect(127.0.0.1:19090)  →  [SSH reverse tunnel]  →  server.accept() on :9090
The client calls a plain TCP connect(). It just happens to land on a loopback port that SSH is listening on and transparently forwarding to the host.

Local mode:


client  →  connect(<HOST_IP>:9090)  →  server.accept() on :9090
Direct TCP socket, no tunnel involved.

So in both cases it is a regular TCP socket connection — the client has no awareness of the tunnel. The SSH reverse tunnel is invisible to both the client and the server; it just moves the TCP bytes between the two machines. The client binary literally does something equivalent to:

connect(fd, &addr_127_0_0_1_19090, sizeof(addr));send(fd, crypto_bundle, bundle_len, 0);
The tunnel endpoint box in the diagram only exists to make the indirection visible — without it the diagram would look like the board client magically skips across machines.